This development would probably facilitate the increasingly likely way out of the election result, i.e. the renewal of the SP<0xC3><0x96> and <0xC3><0x96>VP grand coalition.
In view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Austrian Freedom Party (FP<0xC3><0x96>) obtained 18 percent of the votes and the BZ<0xC3><0x96> gained 11 percent of the votes in 2005 - the Social Democrats, at the same time, expressed their fears about the repetition of the EU sanctions in 1999, when the People's Party agreed to co-governance.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party and I assume that he can return to national politics in Vienna, obviously expects this solution.
The Green Party also entered the parliament, but it lost some of its popularity and fell from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties exceeded the four-percent threshold and did not enter parliament.
