Czech judges in the fight for the seabed
He steps up to the walled electronic map showing Australia and neighboring marine areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a point disappearing in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia and with it the neighboring seabed.
The area is as big as the continent itself,” says Luigi Santosuosso, an Italian lawyer who is part of the UN’s Ocean and Law of the Sea team of 30 lawyers.
His boss, Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, the director of the division, follows the explanation, which is sometimes supplemented.
There is enthusiasm and enthusiasm here.
The seabed hides a world rich in natural resources, little known until now.
Oil, ore and other minerals can be found here, but so far also unknown living organisms, which may be the key to the development of anti-cancer drugs, for example.
Larger than land seabed
The coastal states are now intensively applying for new undersea areas.
According to the United Nations Convention, they are exercising their rights, which was agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is primarily the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends up to a few hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
Such a country shall have exclusive rights under the Convention to all the sources of the continental shelf.
"To put it simply, we consider that part of the seabed and the bottom layer of the continental shelf that is the natural continuation of the seabed.
It extends beyond the borders of the coastal sea, often 200 nautical miles beyond the so-called exclusive economic zone,” Mikulka explains.
The request, submitted by a country to the Commission for the External Borders of the Continental Shelf, should be accompanied by extensive scientific and technical documentation based on a number of costly research and measurements.
This is the result of many years of preparatory work.
“One of our tasks is to provide legal and technical assistance to the committee.
The Commission has so far examined five applications, including those from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," Mikulka adds.
Australia’s recent success has been the first to significantly expand its sub-continent.
But New Zealand also won - the seabed area awarded to it by the commission is about 1.6 million square kilometers, that is, six times the size of the country's territory.
Both countries invested millions of dollars in research.
The profits from future use of the seabed will, they hope, be incalculable.
Other countries are also submitting their applications on a regular basis.
They can do so within ten years of the moment of the ratification of the "Montego Bay Agreement".
Where the continental pedestal ends, the ocean floor area declared by the treaty to be the “common heritage of humanity” begins.
No country has an exclusive status here.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by the international institution established by the Convention.
“The seabed, however, is not Klondike,” says Director Mikulka, exaggerating that “some areas are legally clearly delineated and their regime is contractually fixed.”
Czechs in the Pacific
Today, part of the seabed belongs to the Czech Republic.
This is shared with other countries of the former Eastern Bloc in the framework of the joint "Interoceanmetal" organization.
This organization was granted the so-called “pioneer investor” status under the agreement in 1991, similarly to investors of some other countries.
It is licensed to grow in the ClarionClipperton zone between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati in the Pacific Ocean.
The area inspected by the investor is slightly larger than that of former Czechoslovakia.
The seabed is divided there, it is a kind of undersea copy of the Tatras.
"These can be cultivated on a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area is a rich source of polymetallic ores containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," says another lawyer, Pakshi Rajan.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian associate of the division, presents another example of a concretism.
