Managers are registering more and more bookings.
It’s a good winter for German tour operators.
According to a study, traffic for the coming months increased significantly compared to the previous year – by more than 30 percent for the winter season.
Despite the weak outlook for economic activity, the study found that the German appetite for travel did not wane.
The German Travel Association (DRV) said on Monday that travel agencies saw a 31% increase in their winter bookings compared to the previous year.
According to the GfK market research institute, the number of bookings in the autumn months is even higher.
The turnover of travel agencies in October was 11 percent higher than in October 2007, the DRV said.
These results are based on GfK data, which evaluates the monthly booking data of 1,200 German travel agencies and then extrapolates it to the entire market.
The Institute took into account the trips booked until the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar exchange rate, trips to the US are particularly in demand, the DRV said.
Here, the number of reservations increased by a third.
Germany’s most popular destinations are Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as its domestic landscapes.
“Organised routes are the most sought after,” said Klaus Laepple, president of the DRV.
Due to rising energy and food costs, organized travel costs can be "calculated better for passengers than for individually organized travel."
Passengers can save money with pre-booking discounts or all-inclusive offers, Laepple added.
The booking rate for the summer months was also very good, so it will be possible to book an increase in traffic again compared to the previous year - although according to another study, fewer German tourists undertook travel compared to the previous year.
