Turkey's Expanding Diplomatic Horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps only 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial quest.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed in Neo-Renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the travel books say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms, with one tower at each of the front corners, and looks like some kind of German country town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is a little dilapidated.
However, looking inside the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what a grand enterprise this was the westernmost gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the “late future” of conquests, wanted to use this railway from Damascus to Baghdad to present-day Saudi Arabia to realize its ambitions to conquer the Middle East.
The German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha station was no better.
In 1917, an ammunition train exploded and destroyed the beautifully crafted roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, a sabotage operation was carried out.
Since then, it has slowly decayed and history has far surpassed it.
At the same time, today, as the gateway to the railways towards Anatolia and the entire eastern region, at least symbolically, it serves as Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq, with Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I took the night train to Ankara, the capital of Turkey, to visit Suat Kiniklioglu, one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish MP.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of thumping, which also gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended as a symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, which is known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This raised some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern, stone-and-steel, purpose-built building - located in a developing suburb, between half-finished shopping malls and coffee houses. In the latter, middle managers in suits - both men and women - meet to make a deal early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been a right- and middle-minded politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
“The party’s foreign policy objective is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has disrupted order,” he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
Today it had to face east and west at the same time.
He didn't get to choose between the two.
They had to open in both directions.
"But is it possible that sooner or later he will be forced to choose?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted to face a choice."
He then stressed what almost everyone I have spoken to here has almost mechanically repeated: Turkey’s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea, benefit Europe and the United States as much as Turkey itself.
It is as if they are trying to convey the message that, metaphorically speaking, along with Turkey, the whole of Europe can reach Asia and the Middle East on those eastward railway lines.
When I was at Hydarpasha station again, after another night, mostly awake, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, the two German gentlemen who watched the construction of this ornate structure 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that at the time Turkey was called “the sick man of Europe.”
At that time, there was no question as to which continent would claim this exciting country.
Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes that Vernon "Tod" Handley (born 11 September 1962) has led the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir as the Guildford Music Director.
Based on his musical plans for the area, he founded his wonderful youth choir Proteus the following year.
In principle, only those under the age of 21 could have belonged to the choir, but when Proteus sang its finale in 1979 - many of us were in our late 20s - we simply refused to part with the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the name of the mythological shape-shifter) was in line with the choir's determination and ability to cope with any score that was placed before it - be it a madrigal or a Messiaen piece; without accompaniment, or accompanied by a large orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir has often been amazing and always exciting, and we owe it to the person for whose inspiration our enthusiasm for music has remained unchanged over the years.
How often did Tod tell us to "let the music speak for itself"?
He always said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the score.
So sing it!"
His technique as a conductor was always perfectly understandable and precise, but never dictatorial or excessive.
No matter how good the music was, he was always uplifting.
John Frayn Turner wrote:
If there ever was a choirmaster who should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the two decades he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
In the past 40 years, I have written reviews of more than 100 of his concerts, but he has never disappointed me with any of them and often inspired me with them.
Tod Handley had greatness and modesty together, which is very rare.
He hated the conductors who, in his own words, simply "galled around the world with one or two well-known battlehorses."
Many of us will miss him.
