A second sales record for Honda.
In November, Honda will begin selling the second generation of Jazz.
It is true that its predecessor already had a large enough passenger area, but the interior of the new model is even more spacious.
All this is combined with sophisticated mechanics that make driving more comfortable and increase fuel savings.
Evolution vs. Revolution.
This is what the second generation of Honda Jazz looks like.
Although the new Jazz looks very similar to its predecessor, a number of internal changes have been made.
These include innovative design, new bodywork, larger dimensions and new mechanics.
But before we get into the details of the new model, we have to say that the new Jazz was released six years after the first generation was launched.
So, first of all, we can say that Honda managed to renew this model in a shorter time than other manufacturers.
Jazz is less well-known in Europe, but it is breaking sales records in other markets.
Such a market is Japan, where Jazz was the most popular car brand in 2002 and again in 2008.
In Japan, for example, almost one million jazz pieces have been sold since its launch.
The second market was the Old Continent, with nearly half a million copies sold in six years.
However, with the new Jazz, Honda wants to further increase traffic in the region.
That is, while in 2007 the Japanese company sold a total of 83,000 Jazz cars, by 2009 the target is to sell an estimated 100,000 cars, which would result in a 17% growth in the European market.
Since 2002, Honda has sold 8,000 Jazz cars in the Spanish market, accounting for 6.7% of Honda’s total sales in Spain.
In the case of the new generation, the managers of the Spanish subsidiary are calculated on the basis of 2000 copies sold within a year.
What’s more, the arrival of the new Jazz will greatly ease Honda’s decline in traffic in Spain.
The company expects to sell 22,000 copies by the end of this year, which is 4,000 fewer than in 2007, a decrease of 16%.
Despite sales conditions, Honda increased its market share in Spain to 1.8%, up from 1.6% last year.
By 2010, this figure will also be increased to 2%.
Honda hopes to achieve this by introducing a new model.
This would be the Insight, a five-door, compact-size hybrid with a length of 4,370 mm, of which the Japanese company would sell 200,000 units worldwide each year.
According to the Japanese manufacturer, 50% of Insight's market share would be held by the United States, while the rest would be held by the Old Continent and Japan.
The commercial launch of Insight is due in the first months of the year after the official launch in Valencia, scheduled for January.
Compared to the first generation, the new Jazz has become more spacious in every way.
Its length reaches 3900 mm (five centimeters longer), its width is 1690 mm (two centimeters wider), and the wheelbase is increased by five centimeters, that is, 2500 mm.
Its height remains unchanged at 1520 mm.
In addition to the dimensions, the passenger compartment has also become more spacious.
The larger interior is guaranteed on the one hand by the new body and on the other hand by the fuel tank in the middle – a solution that we already know from the previous Jazz.
In addition, the so-called double-floor trunk’s total cargo volume has increased, currently 399 litres, i.e. 19 litres more than the capacity of the first generation.
This includes the 1.4-engined version, as the 1.2-litre Honda Jazz has a 379-litre boot.
Some exterior modifications can also be discovered, such as rear led lights or an optional panoramic glass roof, as well as easier access to the rear seats.
In addition, the opening angle of the doors for the rear seats was raised to 80 degrees, as opposed to the 67-degree opening angle of the front Jazz.
The engines of the second generation Jazz are also new.
At the beginning of its distribution, this small model is available with two engines of 1.2 and 1.4 liters.
Thanks to i-VTEC technology, both engines consume more power than the previous model and are characterised by lower CO2 emissions and excellent mechanical compatibility, while at the same time the engine delivers outstanding performance in every respect.
The 1.2-liter engine has a power output of 90 hp at 6,000 rpm and a maximum torque of 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
This engine, which had 78 hp in the previous Jazz, consumes 5.3 liters and emits 125 grams of CO2.
The other engine, which produced 83 horsepower in the previous generation, now reaches 100 horsepower.
The 100 hp 1.4 Jazz consumes an average of 5.4 liters and emits 128 grams of CO2.
The "Honeymoon"
For the development of accident prevention technology, Nissan took inspiration from nature, specifically the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company has designed a robot that imitates the flight of bees to avoid accidents.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, may be the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Engineering Center, in collaboration with the renowned University of Tokyo’s Advanced Science and Technology Research Center, have built this little robot in Japan.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Brand Director of Technology PR and Research Development, defines the BR23C as a further extension of Nissan’s four-tier safety envelope.
The robot enhances the collision avoidance capability of the company’s products.
During flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety cover.
Much more important, however, is the complex eye of the uterus, which sees at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions. Consequently, the uterus can fly undisturbed in its own personal space.
To replicate the function of the compound eye, the engineers designed a so-called laser range finder.
In front of the BR23C, the instrument detects obstacles up to 2 metres in front of the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation.
“As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot immediately changes direction by imitating the movements of the bee by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid collision.
The main difference between the system and the currently available instruments is that in this case the bypass manoeuvre takes place completely automatically.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the detour cannot be directed upwards or downwards, nor can it move diagonally, but only in two dimensions, and only in the direction of the turning of the wheels, that is, not in an infinite direction and way, as is the case with bees.
Therefore, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan has implemented a rotation function in the robot to avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process and respond to data every few seconds.
There is no need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may sound surprising, but we’re not talking about gigabytes, or even megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of instant collision prevention technology, which Nissan estimates could be introduced to production vehicles within ten years.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system could be an additional application to get the driver to their destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
