Morgan Stanley Opens Its Capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced a stake in Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG). The largest Japanese bank is paying $9 billion for 21% of the company’s capital after Morgan Stanley shares plummeted in the stock market.
A week after the pre-agreement was announced, the two banks said MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s ordinary shares at a unit price of $25.25, or $3 billion in total.
The agreed price is more than 19% below the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG invests an additional $6 billion in convertible securities, which provide it with a 10% return and an exchange rate of $31.25.
According to Morgan Stanley, the global transaction will be executed at an average exchange rate of $29, which is 28% higher than the current exchange rate.
However, Morgan Stanley's stock price fell by 6.79% at 5 p.m. GMT, closing at $23.07.
“This strategic alliance offers Morgan Stanley a great opportunity to accelerate its transformation into a bank holding company,” said John Mack, CEO of Morgan Stanley.
Morgan Stanley approved the new status last week, which allows it to diversify its activities, while at the same time coming under the control of the Federal Reserve.
The agreement with MUFG reaffirms that the current financial crisis requires even greater caution from corporate giants listed on Wall Street.
The terms announced on Monday also show that the agreement has been amended in recent days: last Monday, Morgan only announced that it will sell 20% of its shares to the Japanese company for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, we thought that the share would consist entirely of ordinary shares,” said Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG in Tokyo.
"However, given the current market and economic situation, we wanted to minimise and avoid potential risks."
In terms of weighted average price, MUFG pays 7% more than book value for Morgan Stanley shares.
As a result of the transaction, the return per share is reduced by approximately 20%.
Under the agreement, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into ordinary shares in one year’s time if the latter’s trading price exceeds the exchange rate by more than 50% over a specified period, i.e. it rises to approximately $47.
Morgan Stanley thus ensures that with funds from MUFG, you can take advantage of your investment opportunities, improve your balance sheet and increase your liquid resources.
A spokesman for the group, however, did not want to give precise information about the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following the merger of MUFG, Morgan Stanley is expected to increase its Tier I solvency ratio by about 15%, making it one of the best in its sector.
Morgan said its balance sheet had "decisively" improved since the end of August.
The past few weeks have been a great ordeal for the group, as the price of its shares has fallen by half, while the cost of its insurance against non-payment risk has skyrocketed.
This cost decreased on Monday, but remained at a high level of around 12%.
Only one “survivor” of the big investment banks remains after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch. This is Goldman Sachs, which announced last week that it had received $15 billion: part of which comes from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group of companies.
Statement by Rafael Correa, Quito
The reconstruction of the republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is the joint plan of Hugo Chavez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Following the example of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa set out his vision for the new constitution on Sunday.
He fulfilled his mission successfully, as 64% of the voters voted in favour of the referendum, according to the official results, which applied to 80% of the votes.
According to this, 28% of the population voted no, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% of them were cast uncompleted.
50% + 1 vote was required for the adoption of the draft Constitution.
On Sunday, two polls at the polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organization showed a massive majority of "yes" votes, with 63% and 70%, respectively.
Rafael Correa has already spoken about the victory of his draft constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution has been a landslide victory," he said, thanking the Ecuadoreans at Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
According to a report by the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, the vote took place in a relaxed atmosphere. The main topic was a text with 444 points summarizing the principles of the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The proposed constitution places state power at the service of the economy, while the state reserves the right to “plan development” for a country that basically lives off oil production by foreign companies and foreign exchange sent by emigrants.
Correa’s 2006 draft constitution also strengthens the power of the head of state, who can obtain a mandate for a maximum of two consecutive terms and has the right to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he wants to make use of this opportunity, and in February 2009 he will once again compete for the presidency.
The president has already started to implement this in his country, which has a population of 13.9 million, and half of the population lives below the subsistence level.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits the presence of foreign troops in the country, which could put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of the Ecuadorian facility that is the basis for US anti-drug measures.
19 hostages freed in Chad
An Egyptian commando attacked the kidnappers, who took 11 tourists and their eight companions hostage ten days ago.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and eight Egyptian escorts were detained for ten days in the desert and transported unharmed to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were freed in the morning by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
They arrived at al-Maza military base, which is directly connected to Cairo International Airport, in good condition, at about half past three in the afternoon.
The hostages were banned from speaking to the press and were immediately transferred to a hospital in Maadi, a suburb of Cairo, where they were examined.
The hostages are “healthy” and the kidnappers “have not been paid a ransom,” Egyptian tourism minister Zoheir Garanna said at the airport.
The hostages were captured on 19 September at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border region of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they were on an off-road safari. The group was then dragged from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown hostage takers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman), as well as eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the safari travel agency Aegyptous.
According to an Egyptian security official, a special commando of 30 people arrived on the scene in two helicopters, where they raided the hostage-takers just before dawn.
"There was a firefight between the troops, half of the kidnappers were killed and the rest fled," the leader said.
He also said that a total of 150 special forces from the Egyptian Lightning Brigade were sent to Sudan, where German and Italian commandos were added.
The Italian diplomatic leader Franco Frattini, who is currently in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and special Italian task forces.
“We must recognize that this result could not have been achieved without the professional and effective intervention of our intelligence personnel and task forces,” he said.
He also denied any ransom was paid for the hostages.
The previous day, the Sudanese army announced that it had intercepted an off-road vehicle carrying the kidnappers, killing six of them, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed that the hostage-takers were linked to the Sudanese Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a rebel group in Darfur, which the organization immediately denied.
Lettres - The "Silent Majority" of Culture
At present, the focus of newspaper news and the ongoing election campaign is the debate on the financing of culture.
We can only rejoice in that.
But a slice of our cultural life is still being forgotten.
Who is going to raise their voice to highlight the ridiculous sums of money that small museums, archives, archaeological excavations and national historical sites are on the verge of starvation.
Which politician dares to remind the federal government that he does not care about his monuments and buildings that are part of the cultural heritage?
Or the fact that there are no laws in Quebec or Canada that actually ensure the effective protection of our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government spent three and a half million euros on the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley alone?
And the Constitution of our American neighbors states that the protection of cultural heritage is a part of American culture, and that this heritage must be protected in a coordinated manner by all citizens, all elected representatives, and all government agencies.
In the framework of the Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec (Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec), more than 40,000 volunteers from 211 societies dealing with history, cultural heritage, archiving and genealogy are engaged in the research of history and the preservation of a large number of private archives and archaeological finds with a minimum budget.
Often, these organizations are tooth and nail defending our heritage and protesting with the last shred of drowning as property developers and policymakers direct their bulldozers towards our old buildings and forgotten cemeteries.
When will anyone stand up for the protection of historical and cultural heritage?
The Benelux governments nationalize a part of Fortis bank
The Benelux countries are helping with partial nationalisation on the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortison, which was the first European to be in trouble due to the spillover effect of the US credit market crisis: the three countries are supporting the financial and insurance institution with a total of 11.2 billion euros.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held talks at the highest level on the matter at the end of the week, involving the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s Competition Commissioner.
In the euro area, Fortis Bank is facing its first major crisis in the wake of an international financial market crisis that has been raging for more than a year, and its decisions can therefore be regarded as precedential in some respects.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, all three states will buy nearly half (49 percent) of the bank’s existing assets there.
The bank will certainly sell some of its interests, including, in particular, those acquired from the Dutch company ABN Amro last year, mainly insurance.
Fortis shares started to plummet last week, and in the second half of the week there were serious crises at the institute.
Analysts agree, however, that with 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
On Friday, the company’s stock fell by about 12 percent to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
In terms of current share prices, the group has a total market capitalisation of around EUR 14 billion, but this is not realistic according to the company directors.
The management blamed overseas market uncertainties related to the adoption of the US $700 billion package plan for the fall of Fortis shares.
By Monday, the papers had risen slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but so far no one has come forward with a meaningful offer.
The Belgian government has already indicated that investors do not have to worry about losing their money.
So far, there has been no panic among the bank’s clients, and the branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has its own branch and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the henhouse
In the United States, life and health insurers often refuse to take out an insurance contract based on people’s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a data protection program that always makes the use of prescription data subject’s consent.
It has to be in independent hands, otherwise we leave the henhouse to the fox,” Richard Dick, the developer of the drug prescription tracking program, told The Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of damage dependent on the health of the applicant customer, and if they consider the risk too great, they do not even take out insurance with it.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only with the knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick came up with a much cheaper method: he could easily get the drugs he had bought in the past year and a half from pharmacies based on the customer’s ID number, and the program itself would infer the disease he was suffering from and the state of his health.
For example, if you regularly take high doses of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it indicates that you have virtually uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program on the market, some of which also determine a risk multiplier, so the insurer has little to do outside of the paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can be used for multiple purposes, for example, some compounds can be used against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, the former not.
Separate companies have been formed for the retrieval and processing of the data, and before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, they ask the patient’s consent.
They are now obliged to do so by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their failure to do so.
More recently, some companies are processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data, so they can provide an even more accurate picture of the patients’ health status.
More and more companies have access to the data, and at the same time it will become more and more difficult to control the use of the data.
There is a separate health data protection law, but it only applies to health care providers and insurers.
There is a bill in front of the Congress that gives the authorities control over companies specialising in data provision.
Dick Richard admits that this is not enough: he has therefore further developed his programme, which would make the transfer of data subject’s explicit consent subject to it.
Another issue is that the person concerned can hardly refuse the consent, otherwise the insurers will not enter into a contract with him.
So the hens are somehow dependent on the fox's benevolence.
The Global Marseille Menu
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
As the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this issue dominated the agenda of the ninth summit, alongside other, largely global, issues.
There will also be a French-Indian summit today, which will focus on nuclear energy cooperation.
The European Union recognises that India is an emerging democratic power that should have a greater say in international affairs, but member states have not yet reached a consensus on whether to support New Delhi’s permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This question was therefore not raised at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as President-in-Office of the Council of the European Union, and Commission President José Manuel Barroso and High Representative Javier Solana welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade to more than 100 billion euros in five years.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious target.
In this spirit, the 26 bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have been legally consolidated, meaning that air traffic may also soar in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the talks.
The aim is to balance the fact that while the EU is India's number one trading partner, New Delhi is only the ninth in the EU's list of partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, as well as terrorism, were condemned in all its forms on both sides and called for a UN conference to be convened.
They also called for an end to the Doha trade round, although both have played a large part in the failure so far.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, which aims to reduce emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India has also agreed that a global deal should be reached at next year’s climate conference and greenhouse gas production should be cut by 50% by 2050.
They also want to prevent the rise in food prices and have supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister is heading to the French capital today, where he is preparing to make a deal on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will be awarded 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
The news agency said the deal would last for 15 years.
More than 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
There is a strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishing houses will be present at the 60th Buchmesse, the most important international copyright fair.
7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries are expected to attend this year’s Frankfurt International Book Fair, covering an area of 171,790 square metres, where more than 403,000 books will be presented.
At the opening ceremony of the Italian Pavilion, the Italian Government will be represented by Francesco Maria Giro, Deputy State Secretary for Cultural Goods and Activities, as Italy will occupy 264 square metres of exhibition space by setting up a single Italia Point.
The opening ceremony will be followed by a press conference in the "Room Structur" room of the Buchmesse 5.0 pavilion, where the state of Italian publishing will be presented with data, trends and prospects.
According to the data, the share of foreign authors in the Italian publishing market is constantly decreasing, especially in the field of adult and youth publications.
Billionaire Steve Fossett's plane has been found.
The remains of billionaire Steve Fossett, who disappeared over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007, have been found.
The wreckage was found on a 3,000-meter-high plateau in the Mammoth Lakes region of the Sierra Nevada Mountains, on the border between California and Nevada.
No human remains were found inside the aircraft.
John Anderson, sheriff of Madera County, said: “After determining the location of the plane, we have sent out a team and can now be sure that it is the plane that Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff also confirmed that no human remains were found in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Transportation Security Administration (NTSB) said a few hours after the wreck was discovered, a search committee was called in to identify the plane and determine that it was indeed the Bellanca 8kcab that went missing on September 3, 2007, the day Fossett left Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett’s personal belongings near his home in Mammoth Lakes.
Two I.D.s in Fosset's name, issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, some cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was abandoned a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire has set a number of summits through which he has written himself into history.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he was able to fly around the earth for the first time with a balloon: two weeks of solitary flight.
Three years later, he circled the earth by plane without landing.
Among his many records is a flight over the Andes at an altitude of 15.445 meters, which he performed with a co-pilot.
GLK, shocking advertising
An unusual, yet original and distinctly formal recreational vehicle with large surfaces and clean corners.
In a few words, this is the latest "compact off-road vehicle" from Mercedes-Benz, with which the German car manufacturer tried to bring fresh impetus to the market.
It is precisely because of this unconventional content that the introductory campaign for the SUV GLK available in Mercedes-Benz showrooms from October 17 will be surprising and unusual.
The advertising campaign accompanying the introduction of the new vehicle uses a hitherto unknown media-communication tool, including utopian 3D posters that have not been used by a car brand in Italy.
The billboard action, which consists of three stages, will dominate Milan’s central shopping street, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of media communication begins with a three-dimensional presentation of the car, in which the new SUV, with the help of special glasses distributed around Corso Como, will be seen in almost real sizes and in three-dimensional form.
When you look at the picture, it will feel as if the car is coming out of the poster.
Then, thanks to the innovative Elumina8 technology, every detail of the new GLK becomes visible one by one and then becomes a unified image.
Undoubtedly, with this promotion Mercedes is trying to introduce something new to the stereotypical advertising world of the automotive industry.
Will it be able to attract the attention of future customers? We’ll see.
